{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4fb4e553-84bf-4aa9-b333-4342cc720426","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in a minimal image, copy the tool from a sidecar or use `kubectl cp` to bring in a self-contained build.\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want a browser-viewable flamegraph without Windows tooling.\n- For production, consider **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection without exec'ing in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f18d7d0c-67e7-4983-b079-d3c856d87eae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":300},"id":"67041d7b-4234-46b8-aa1c-51769204ea1c","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:33.799Z","parentId":"72d53012-c527-47c7-8722-84003d4475aa"}
